webpackJsonp([0xfa4d58043b69],{751:function(e,a){e.exports={data:{post:{id:"/home/travis/build/simonagren/simonagren.github.io/content/posts/2020-03-11--azcli-connection/index.md absPath of file >>> MarkdownRemark",html:'<p>\n  <a\n    class="gatsby-resp-image-link"\n    href="/static/azcli-connection-fba499085724398a27f00be5af554b7e-b70ec.png"\n    style="display: block"\n    target="_blank"\n    rel="noopener"\n  >\n  \n  <span\n    class="gatsby-resp-image-wrapper"\n    style="position: relative; display: block; ; max-width: 800px; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto;"\n  >\n    <span\n      class="gatsby-resp-image-background-image"\n      style="padding-bottom: 46.916666666666664%; position: relative; bottom: 0; left: 0; background-image: url(\'data:image/png;base64,\'); background-size: cover; display: block;"\n    >\n      <img\n        class="gatsby-resp-image-image"\n        style="width: 100%; height: 100%; margin: 0; vertical-align: middle; position: absolute; top: 0; left: 0; box-shadow: inset 0px 0px 0px 400px transparent;"\n        alt="extend"\n        title=""\n        src="/static/azcli-connection-fba499085724398a27f00be5af554b7e-48538.png"\n        srcset="/static/azcli-connection-fba499085724398a27f00be5af554b7e-bed0f.png 200w,\n/static/azcli-connection-fba499085724398a27f00be5af554b7e-5fd34.png 400w,\n/static/azcli-connection-fba499085724398a27f00be5af554b7e-48538.png 800w,\n/static/azcli-connection-fba499085724398a27f00be5af554b7e-b70ec.png 1200w"\n        sizes="(max-width: 800px) 100vw, 800px"\n      />\n    </span>\n  </span>\n  \n  </a>\n    </p>\n<p>In the previous post <a href="https://simonagren.github.io/azcli-adscope" target="_blank">Azure AD &#x26; Microsoft Graph permission scopes, with Azure CLI</a>, we registered an Azure AD Application using specific scopes to the service principal <code class="language-text">Microsoft Graph</code>. We also prepared it with a reply-URL that works for Bot Framework auth.</p>\n<p>In this post we will create an <code class="language-text">OAuth connection</code> from the Bot Channels Registration to the Azure AD Registration, giving the Bot the possibility to get a token to call Microsoft Graph.</p>\n<h1>Prerequisites</h1>\n<ul>\n<li><a href="https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/cli/azure/install-azure-cli">Azure Cli</a></li>\n<li><a href="https://azure.microsoft.com/free/">An Azure Account</a></li>\n</ul>\n<h1>Create command</h1>\n<p>When we use the command <a href="https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/cli/azure/bot/authsetting?view=azure-cli-latest#az-bot-authsetting-create">az bot authsetting create</a> there are some common things we need to enter such as: </p>\n<ul>\n<li><code class="language-text">--resource-group</code></li>\n<li><code class="language-text">--name</code></li>\n<li><code class="language-text">--setting-name</code></li>\n<li><code class="language-text">--provider-scope-string</code></li>\n<li><code class="language-text">--client-id</code></li>\n<li><code class="language-text">--client-secret</code>. </li>\n</ul>\n<p>Depending on which <code class="language-text">--service</code> (service provider) you decide to use there are a few service-specific things we need to add in <code class="language-text">--parameters</code>. </p>\n<p>As you can see in the picture with <strong>Azure Active Directory V2</strong> we need to add a <code class="language-text">Tenant ID</code>.</p>\n<p>\n  <a\n    class="gatsby-resp-image-link"\n    href="/static/new-ac64472397bab364106edb2e74110704-c0333.png"\n    style="display: block"\n    target="_blank"\n    rel="noopener"\n  >\n  \n  <span\n    class="gatsby-resp-image-wrapper"\n    style="position: relative; display: block; ; max-width: 392px; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto;"\n  >\n    <span\n      class="gatsby-resp-image-background-image"\n      style="padding-bottom: 151.0204081632653%; position: relative; bottom: 0; left: 0; background-image: url(\'data:image/png;base64,\'); background-size: cover; display: block;"\n    >\n      <img\n        class="gatsby-resp-image-image"\n        style="width: 100%; height: 100%; margin: 0; vertical-align: middle; position: absolute; top: 0; left: 0; box-shadow: inset 0px 0px 0px 400px transparent;"\n        alt="newconn"\n        title=""\n        src="/static/new-ac64472397bab364106edb2e74110704-c0333.png"\n        srcset="/static/new-ac64472397bab364106edb2e74110704-918e4.png 200w,\n/static/new-ac64472397bab364106edb2e74110704-c0333.png 392w"\n        sizes="(max-width: 392px) 100vw, 392px"\n      />\n    </span>\n  </span>\n  \n  </a>\n    </p>\n<h2>We need some more things</h2>\n<p>At first, I tried to create the OAuth connection with the common properties and only <code class="language-text">tenantId=&lt;tenantId&gt;</code>in the property string. </p>\n<p>The connection seemed to work just fine, although, from the UI in the portal, the Client id, and Client secret were blank.</p>\n<p>\n  <a\n    class="gatsby-resp-image-link"\n    href="/static/workingbut-e5951395257500016a846af2f18fcc5d-338ff.png"\n    style="display: block"\n    target="_blank"\n    rel="noopener"\n  >\n  \n  <span\n    class="gatsby-resp-image-wrapper"\n    style="position: relative; display: block; ; max-width: 386px; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto;"\n  >\n    <span\n      class="gatsby-resp-image-background-image"\n      style="padding-bottom: 158.80829015544043%; position: relative; bottom: 0; left: 0; background-image: url(\'data:image/png;base64,\'); background-size: cover; display: block;"\n    >\n      <img\n        class="gatsby-resp-image-image"\n        style="width: 100%; height: 100%; margin: 0; vertical-align: middle; position: absolute; top: 0; left: 0; box-shadow: inset 0px 0px 0px 400px transparent;"\n        alt="workingbut"\n        title=""\n        src="/static/workingbut-e5951395257500016a846af2f18fcc5d-338ff.png"\n        srcset="/static/workingbut-e5951395257500016a846af2f18fcc5d-04a2c.png 200w,\n/static/workingbut-e5951395257500016a846af2f18fcc5d-338ff.png 386w"\n        sizes="(max-width: 386px) 100vw, 386px"\n      />\n    </span>\n  </span>\n  \n  </a>\n    </p>\n<p>This made no sense since I had provided the <code class="language-text">--client-id</code> and <code class="language-text">--client-secret</code> in the creation. </p>\n<p>Turns out the <strong>Azure Active Directory V2</strong> service takes more <code class="language-text">--parameters</code> key-value pairs:</p>\n<ul>\n<li><code class="language-text">clientId</code></li>\n<li><code class="language-text">clientSecret</code></li>\n<li><code class="language-text">tenantId</code></li>\n</ul>\n<p>If you provide all of them everything will be fine!</p>\n<h1>List all available service providers</h1>\n<p>We use the command <code class="language-text">az bot authsetting list-providers</code> to get all service providers. </p>\n<p>We also add a query <code class="language-text">--query &quot;value[].[properties.displayName, properties.serviceProviderNamme]&quot;</code> to get the display name and the service provider name, and output it as a table.</p>\n<div class="gatsby-highlight" data-language="powershell">\n      <pre class="language-powershell"><code class="language-powershell">az bot authsetting list<span class="token operator">-</span>providers <span class="token operator">--</span>query <span class="token string">"value[].[properties.displayName, properties.serviceProviderName]"</span> <span class="token operator">-</span>o table</code></pre>\n      </div>\n<h1>Use the service provider name in a variable</h1>\n<p>You could of course just copy the service provider name from the table we printed. </p>\n<p>If you are running Azure CLI from PowerShell, like I am, this is an example to grab the Azure Active Directory service provider name to a variable.</p>\n<div class="gatsby-highlight" data-language="powershell">\n      <pre class="language-powershell"><code class="language-powershell"><span class="token variable">$providerName</span> = az bot authsetting list<span class="token operator">-</span>providers <span class="token operator">--</span>query <span class="token string">"value[?properties.displayName==\'Azure Active Directory v2\'].properties.serviceProviderName | [0]"</span> </code></pre>\n      </div>\n<h1>Creating an OAuth connection setting</h1>\n<p>In this example, we create a connection setting to an Azure AD V2 application. The registered Azure Active Directory Application has permissions to the Microsoft Graph.</p>\n<ol>\n<li>Create variables</li>\n</ol>\n<div class="gatsby-highlight" data-language="powershell">\n      <pre class="language-powershell"><code class="language-powershell"><span class="token variable">$clientId</span> = <span class="token string">"&lt;IdFromAADapp>"</span> \n<span class="token variable">$clientSecret</span> = <span class="token string">"&lt;secretFromAADapp>"</span>\n<span class="token variable">$tenantId</span> = <span class="token string">"&lt;tenantId>"</span>\n<span class="token variable">$rGroup</span> = <span class="token string">"RGSimonBot"</span>\n<span class="token variable">$botName</span> = <span class="token string">"BotSimonBot"</span>\n<span class="token variable">$connName</span> = <span class="token string">"GraphConnection"</span>\n<span class="token variable">$scopeString</span> = <span class="token string">"openid profile User.Read Group.Read.All"</span></code></pre>\n      </div>\n<ol start="2">\n<li>Get Azure Active Directory V2 service provider name</li>\n</ol>\n<div class="gatsby-highlight" data-language="powershell">\n      <pre class="language-powershell"><code class="language-powershell"><span class="token variable">$providerName</span> = az bot authsetting list<span class="token operator">-</span>providers <span class="token operator">--</span>query <span class="token string">"value[?properties.displayName==\'Azure Active Directory v2\'].properties.serviceProviderName | [0]"</span> </code></pre>\n      </div>\n<ol start="3">\n<li>Create Connection</li>\n</ol>\n<div class="gatsby-highlight" data-language="powershell">\n      <pre class="language-powershell"><code class="language-powershell">az bot authsetting create <span class="token operator">-</span>g <span class="token variable">$rGroup</span> <span class="token operator">-</span>n <span class="token variable">$botName</span> <span class="token operator">-</span>c <span class="token variable">$connName</span> <span class="token operator">--</span>client<span class="token operator">-</span>id <span class="token variable">$clientId</span> <span class="token operator">--</span>client<span class="token operator">-</span>secret <span class="token variable">$clientSecret</span> <span class="token operator">--</span>provider<span class="token operator">-</span>scope<span class="token operator">-</span>string <span class="token variable">$scopeString</span> <span class="token operator">--</span>service <span class="token variable">$providerName</span> <span class="token operator">--</span>parameters <span class="token string">"clientId=<span class="token variable">$clientId</span>"</span> <span class="token string">"clientSecret=<span class="token variable">$clientSecret</span>"</span> <span class="token string">"tenantId=<span class="token variable">$tenantId</span>"</span></code></pre>\n      </div>\n<p>Great! Now you have created the connection, and we could find it from the settings of the Bot Channels registration.</p>\n<p>\n  <a\n    class="gatsby-resp-image-link"\n    href="/static/oauthconn-2ed6b584465db510db4b02da49395810-95975.png"\n    style="display: block"\n    target="_blank"\n    rel="noopener"\n  >\n  \n  <span\n    class="gatsby-resp-image-wrapper"\n    style="position: relative; display: block; ; max-width: 375px; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto;"\n  >\n    <span\n      class="gatsby-resp-image-background-image"\n      style="padding-bottom: 156.26666666666665%; position: relative; bottom: 0; left: 0; background-image: url(\'data:image/png;base64,\'); background-size: cover; display: block;"\n    >\n      <img\n        class="gatsby-resp-image-image"\n        style="width: 100%; height: 100%; margin: 0; vertical-align: middle; position: absolute; top: 0; left: 0; box-shadow: inset 0px 0px 0px 400px transparent;"\n        alt="oauthconn"\n        title=""\n        src="/static/oauthconn-2ed6b584465db510db4b02da49395810-95975.png"\n        srcset="/static/oauthconn-2ed6b584465db510db4b02da49395810-2e141.png 200w,\n/static/oauthconn-2ed6b584465db510db4b02da49395810-95975.png 375w"\n        sizes="(max-width: 375px) 100vw, 375px"\n      />\n    </span>\n  </span>\n  \n  </a>\n    </p>',fields:{slug:"/azcli-connection/",prefix:"2020-03-11"},frontmatter:{title:"Azure AD & Microsoft Graph OAuth Connection, with Azure CLI",author:"Simon Ågren",category:null,tags:["azure","msgraph","botframework"],cover:{childImageSharp:{resize:{src:"/static/azcli-connection-fba499085724398a27f00be5af554b7e-160fa.png"}}}}},authornote:{id:"/home/travis/build/simonagren/simonagren.github.io/content/parts/author.md absPath of file >>> MarkdownRemark",html:"<p><strong>Simon Ågren</strong> Passionate about SharePoint and Office365. Solution Architect working as a consultant for Sogeti in Umeå, Sweden.</p>"},site:{siteMetadata:{facebook:{appId:"2263145610597628"}}}},pathContext:{slug:"/azcli-connection/",prev:{id:"/home/travis/build/simonagren/simonagren.github.io/content/posts/2020-03-09--azcli-adscope/index.md absPath of file >>> MarkdownRemark",fields:{slug:"/azcli-adscope/",prefix:"2020-03-09"},frontmatter:{title:"Azure AD & Microsoft Graph permission scopes, with Azure CLI",category:null,tags:["azure","msgraph","botframework"]}},next:{id:"/home/travis/build/simonagren/simonagren.github.io/content/posts/2020-03-13--azurebot-nodejs-part5/index.md absPath of file >>> MarkdownRemark",fields:{slug:"/azurebot-nodejs-part5/",prefix:"2020-03-13"},frontmatter:{title:"Bot Framework in Node.js - Auth and Microsoft Graph (part 5)",category:null,tags:["botframework","nodejs","azure","msteams","msgraph"]}}}}}});
